# AppStream 2.0 Image Builder

An Image Builder is essentially just an Amazon EC2 instance that you use to create the custom image that contains the applications you would like to stream. Normally, you would have to configure and launch your own Image Builder, but to save you some time, weâ€™ve pre-created one for you in the lab environment. By the end of this step, you will have your applications installed and configured.

If you are using your own account, follow the instructions in **Create Image Builder**.

If you are using an account provided by an AWS facilitator, the image builder has been created for you. Follow the instructions in **Connect to Image Builder**.

## Create Image Builder

Follow these instructions if you are using your own account. If you are using an account provided by an AWS facilitator, these steps have been completed for you.

This workshop uses the US East (N. Virginia), US West (Oregon), or Europe (Ireland) Region. Please refer to the [AWS Regional Products and Services](https://aws.amazon.com/about-aws/global-infrastructure/regional-product-services/)  page for details of Amazon AppStream 2.0 service availability by region.

New! A CloudFormation template to deploy the prerequisites in your own account is available on [GitHub](https://github.com/aws-samples/getting-started-with-amazon-appstream2-workshop-template/) .

**[Create an Image Builder Instance](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imagebuilder/createimagebuilder"%20\l%20"create-an-image-builder-instance)**

AppStream 2.0 uses EC2 instances to stream applications. You launch instances, called image builders, from base images provided by AppStream 2.0. To create your own custom image, you connect to an image builder instance, install and configure your applications for streaming, and then create your image by creating a snapshot of the image builder instance.

To install and configure applications to stream to your users, you must create an image builder instance as described in the following procedure.

**[Create an Image Builder Instance for Adding Applications](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imagebuilder/createimagebuilder"%20\l%20"create-an-image-builder-instance-for-adding-applications)**

1. Open the [Amazon AppStream 2.0 console](https://console.aws.amazon.com/appstream2) .
2. If you have not previously configured any AppStream 2.0 settings, the following page appears:

![Getting Started Amazon AppStream 2.0](data:image/png;base64,)

1. In the navigation pane, choose **Images** and then choose the **Image Builder** tab.
2. Choose **Launch Image Builder**.
3. The Choose an Image window opens. In the Filter by attribute or keyword box, choose **Platform = Microsoft Windows Server 2019 base**.

![Choose an image with the Image Builder](data:image/png;base64,)

1. In the Filter by attribute or keyword box, choose **Instance family = General purpose**.

![Choose an image with the Image Builder](data:image/png;base64,)

1. Select the latest image in the list and choose **Next**. The Image Builder configuration options appear.

![Choose an image with the Image Builder](data:image/png;base64,)

1. Enter the following information in the Configure Image Builder window and choose **Next**.

**[Configure Image Builder fields](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imagebuilder/createimagebuilder"%20\l%20"configure-image-builder-fields)**

| **Option** | **Value** |
| --- | --- |
| **Name** | The unique name identifier for the image builder, such as _DemoCo_Image1_mmddyyyy_. Note the naming syntax below. |
| **Display Name** | The name displayed in the console, such as _DemoCo Image1 Month Year_. |
| **Tags** | Accept the default |
| **Choose instance Type:** | Select **stream.standard.medium**. |
| **IAM roles - _advanced_** | Accept default value. |
| **VPC Endpoints - _advanced_** | Accept default value. |

**[Naming Syntax](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imagebuilder/createimagebuilder"%20\l%20"naming-syntax)**

The **Name** and **Display Name** fields are for identification purposes only. You may use any names that are meaningful to you. The **Name** syntax allows for any combination of characters in these four categories:

- - Lowercase letters (a-z)
    - Uppercase letters (A-Z)
    - Numbers (0-9)
    - Non-alphanumeric characters (_ -)

The **Display Name** syntax does not have these restrictions and can use any non-alphanumeric characters as well as spaces between characters.

1. On the Configure Network page, enter the following and choose **Next**.

**[Configure Network access fields](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imagebuilder/createimagebuilder"%20\l%20"configure-network-access-fields)**

| **Option** | **Value** |
| --- | --- |
| **Default Internet Access** | Leave unchecked |
| **VPC** | AppStream 2 VPC |
| **Subnet 1** | Select the subnet with IP range of 10.0.1.0/24 (AppStream2 Private Subnet 1) |
| **Security group** | Leave _sg-xxxx - default_ selected |
| **Active Directory domain - _optional_** | Accept the default value (not configured) |

1. On the Review and create page, review the details. When you are satisfied, choose **Launch Image builder**.

The Image Builder instance creation process starts. It takes approximately 15 minutes to complete. During this process, your Image Builder instance will show a status of _Pending_ while it is being created. Choose the **Refresh** icon to update the status.

Once the status changes to _Running_, the Image Builder instance has been successfully created. You can proceed to the next section.

![Image Builder Running](data:image/png;base64,)

Charges accrue for an image builder instance while it is running, even if there is no user connected. You can stop or terminate the image builder at any time. There are no additional user fees incurred for admin users connecting to an image builder.

## Connect to Image Builder

**[Connect to an Image Builder](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imagebuilder/launchib"%20\l%20"connect-to-an-image-builder)**

To use the AppStream 2.0 console to connect to an image builder through a web browser, complete the following steps.

1. Open the AppStream 2.0 console at <https://console.aws.amazon.com/appstream2> .
2. In the left navigation pane, choose **Images**. Select the **Image Builder** tab.
3. In the list of image builders, choose the image builder to which you want to connect. Verify that the status of the image builder is **Running**, and choose **Connect**.

![Connect to the Image Builder](data:image/png;base64,)

For this step to work, you might need to configure your browser to allow pop-ups from <https://stream.&lt;aws-region&gt;.amazonappstream.com/>.

1. The new browser tab opens, displaying options for logging into the image builder instance. Choose **Administrator**.

After a few moments, you are connected to a Windows Server instance as a local user who has full administrator privileges. You can proceed with installing the applications.

## Installing Applications

**[Applications](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imagebuilder/apps-install"%20\l%20"applications)**

For this lab, there are 2 applications that we recommend you install.

1. Install the latest version of **Google Chrome**.
2. Install the latest version of **Notepad++**.

**[Installing and configuring applications](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imagebuilder/apps-install"%20\l%20"installing-and-configuring-applications)**

You can install and configure many types of applications for streaming, including:

- Vendor-provided .exe, .msi, .msi with .mst, .iso, etc.
- Browsers with configured URLs and/or required plugins
- Virtualized applications (ThinApp, App-V, layered)

Regardless of the application type, you need to consider how the installation media or files will be accessed for the installation. Options include, but are not limited to:

- Software vendors' websites
- Enterprise application package repositories (e.g. SCCM distribution points)
- File shares (e.g. Amazon FSx)
- Object stores (e.g. Amazon S3)

We suggest that the installation source media or files be centrally consolidated. Here are three recommended options:

- Amazon S3 bucket where media can be downloaded to the image builder instance through a browser
- Locally in a folder on the physical device connecting to the image builder instance through the browser
- A list of direct URLs to vendor installation downloads

**[Download the Application Installation Media](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imagebuilder/apps-install"%20\l%20"download-the-application-installation-media)**

This lab uses the following URLs to download the installation media:

- Google Chrome Enterprise (<https://chromeenterprise.google/browser/download/#windows-tab> )
- Notepad++ (<https://notepad-plus-plus.org/> )

1. Open Firefox by choosing the **Firefox desktop icon**. Since this is the first time, it may prompt you for initial setup steps which may vary.
2. If prompted by the Firefox Import Wizard, choose **Don't import anything** and then choose **Next**.
3. If prompted to set a default browser, choose **Use Firefox as my default browser**. If prompted to decide how to open an HTTP link, choose the Firefox icon to select it.
4. Enter this URL in Firefox to download the full Chrome browser installer: <https://enterprise.google.com/chrome/chrome-browser/> .
5. Select **Channel, Stable. File type, MSI. Architecture 64-bit**.
6. Choose **Download**.
7. When prompted, choose **Accept and download**.
8. When prompted, choose **Save File**. The file is saved to the Downloads folder.
9. Enter this URL in Firefox to download the full Notepad++ installer: <https://notepad-plus-plus.org/downloads>
10. Choose the latest release. Scroll down to _Download 64-bit x64_ section and choose **Installer**.

![NotePad++ Installer](data:image/png;base64,)

1. If prompted, choose **Save File**. The file is saved to the Downloads folder.
2. Close Firefox. Choose **Close tabs** if prompted.

**[Install the Applications](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imagebuilder/apps-install"%20\l%20"install-the-applications)**

1. Open File Explorer by choosing the **folder icon** on the taskbar.
2. Choose the **Downloads** folder to open it. The Google Chrome and Notepad++ installer files that you just downloaded should be listed.

![Installers](data:image/png;base64,)

1. To begin Chrome installation, run _googlechromestandaloneenterprise64.msi_.
2. To begin Notepad++ installation, run _npp.x.x.x.Installer.x64.exe_. Select the default values. When prompted, choose **Finish** to complete the installation.
3. Close Notepad++ and any other open windows.

**[Configure the applications](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imagebuilder/apps-install"%20\l%20"configure-the-applications)**

You have installed the applications from your source media. Now you need to configure and update them.

Examples of tasks or configurations to consider, if applicable, at this stage for each application include:

- Applying any patches or updates
- Managing auto-update functionality
- Reviewing and optimizing any startup or run/runonce commands
- Performance tuning configurations specific to the applications
- Disabling application start up prompts (EULA prompts, First Run Experiences, etc.)
- Validate/configure file associations
- Clearing or resetting of any log files or event logs

Any profile-specific application customized settings (for example, browser favorites or home pages saved through the settings or preferences menu) will not be captured for the applications in your image. Read the vendor documentation to see how to set those default values for new users (.ini file, config.xml, registry key, etc.).

Google Chrome includes an automated update process that is managed through the local task scheduler. For demonstration purposes, we do not want Chrome to update itself automatically because we do not want our end users to see any evidence of that process.

1. Open the Task Scheduler utility.
    - Choose the **Start** button.
    - Choose **Windows Administrative Tools**.

![Windows Administrative Tools](data:image/png;base64,)

- - Open **Task Scheduler**.
    - When Task Scheduler opens, expand the window to full screen for easier viewing.

1. On the left hand side, choose **Task Scheduler Library**.

![Task Scheduler Library](data:image/png;base64,)

1. Select the **GoogleUpdateTaskMachineCore** task to highlight it. On the **Action** menu, choose **Delete**. When prompted, choose **Yes**.
2. Select the remaining Google update task, **GoogleUpdateTaskMachineUA**. On the **Action** menu, choose **Delete**. When prompted, choose **Yes**.

![Delete Tasks](data:image/png;base64,)

1. Close **Task Scheduler**.

Close any other open windows on the desktop. Your applications to stream are installed and properly configured. You can now proceed to the next section.

# Image Assistant

At this point, you have an image builder instance with individual applications installed and configured. Now you need to finalize the applications for streaming, have the Image Assistant optimize them for streaming performance, and create the custom image that streaming instances will be launched from.

## Add Streaming Applications

**[Start Image Assistant and add applications for streaming](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imageassistant/streamapps"%20\l%20"start-image-assistant-and-add-applications-for-streaming)**

This step defines the locally installed applications that will be enabled for streaming. Some of the configurations defined here include name, display name, executable file to launch, and icon to display.

1. Open the Image Assistant by choosing the desktop icon.

![Image Assistant Icon](data:image/png;base64,)

1. The AppStream 2.0 Image Assistant window opens, with the **1\. ADD APPS** tab open. Choose **\+ Add App** so we can add our first application to be streamed.

![Image Assistant](data:image/png;base64,)

1. An Open dialog box opens. Navigate to the location of the Chrome installation (C:\\Program Files\\Google\\Chrome\\Application) and choose **chrome.exe**. Note that the File Name field populates with _chrome_. Choose **Open**.
2. Enter the following information in the Image Assistant Edit Applications Setting window and choose **Save**.

**[Edit Application Setting Fields for Google Chrome](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imageassistant/streamapps"%20\l%20"edit-application-setting-fields-for-google-chrome)**

| **Option** | **Value** |
| --- | --- |
| **Name** | _Chrome_x64_&lt;version&gt;_ |
| **Display Name** | Google Chrome |
| **Launch Path** | Accept default value |
| **Icon Path** | Accept default value |
| **Launch Parameters** | Leave blank |
| **Working Directory** | Leave blank |

1. In the Add Applications to Image window, choose **+Add Application** again to add the second application to stream, Notepad++.
2. An Open dialog box opens. Navigate to the location of the Notepad++ installation (C:\\Program Files\\Notepad++) and choose **notepad++.exe**. Note that the File Name field populates with _notepad++_. Choose **Open**.
3. Enter the following information into the Image Assistant Edit Applications Setting window and choose **Save**.

**[Edit Application Setting Fields for Notepad++](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imageassistant/streamapps"%20\l%20"edit-application-setting-fields-for-notepad++)**

| **Option** | **Value** |
| --- | --- |
| **Name** | _Notepad++\_x64_&lt;version&gt;_ |
| **Display Name** | Notepad++ |
| **Launch Path** | Accept default value |
| **Icon Path** | Accept default value |
| **Launch Parameters** | Leave blank |
| **Working Directory** | Leave blank |

1. Both of the applications are listed in the **1\. ADD APPS** tab of the Image Assistant, so choose **Next**.

![Image Assistant Apps](data:image/png;base64,)

1. While within **CONFIGURE APPS**, we will leave the default app and windows settings as-is. So, Choose **Next**.

![Image Assistant Configure Apps](data:image/png;base64,)

Here, you create default application and Windows settings for your users. We will be skipping this step for this lab in the interests of time. If you would like more information on this, review the Tutorial for Creating Default Application Settings in an Image Builder.

## Validate Applications

**[Validate applications:](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imageassistant/validateapps"%20\l%20"validate-applications:)**

The applications are now installed and configured. For this step, use the **Test User** account to validate them. This is a local account that does not have elevated or local admin privileges, so it will validate the applications launch properly.

1. The focus of the Image Assistant moves to the **3\. TEST** tab. Select **Switch User**.
2. You will be then provided with the different user accounts, as shown below. Choose **Test User**

![Image Builder User Accounts](data:image/png;base64,)

You are now connect to your image builder instance with a local user who has regular end user privileges. You can proceed with validating the applications.

1. Open the Image Assistant by selecting the desktop icon. The **Test Apps** window opens, listing the applications to validate.

![Image Builder User Accounts](data:image/png;base64,)

1. Open the first application, Google Chrome, by choosing it from the Image Assistant.

You must launch the application from the Test Streaming window and not the desktop icon or Start menu.

1. Allow Google Chrome to start up completely and then close it.

Chrome will not retain the Home button or home URL. This profile is ignored when the image is taken, so you do not need to enter it here. This applies to any application.

1. In the **Test Apps** window, choose the second application, Notepad++, to launch it.
2. Allow Notepad++ to start up completely and then close it.
3. Leaving the **Test Applications** window open, ensure that all application windows are closed.
4. In the **Test Apps** window, choose **Switch User** and select **Administrator**.
5. In the Image Assistant's **3\. TEST tab**, choose **Next**.

Weâ€™ve now verified that our applications can successfully launch as a user without elevated or admin privileges.

## Optimize Performance

**[Optimize start-up performance](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imageassistant/optimizeperf"%20\l%20"optimize-start-up-performance)**

In this step, Image Assistant opens your applications one after another, identifies their launch dependencies, and performs optimizations to ensure that applications launch quickly.

Here, "optimize" refers to a behind-the-scenes process that reviews how an application starts up and directs the streaming service as to how best to tune itself to ensure that the app is in a useable state as quickly as possible for end users when they stream it.

1. In Image Assistant, in **4\. Optimize**, choose **Launch**.

![Image Assistant Optimize](data:image/png;base64,)

1. AppStream 2.0 automatically launches the first application in your list. When the application completely starts, provide any required input to perform the first run experience for the application. For example, Google Chrome may prompt you to import settings before it is completely up and running. You can skip through these settings.
2. After you complete the first run experience and verify that the application performs as expected, choose **Continue**. Notepad++, opens automatically. Complete the first run experience and validate your Notepad++ configuration. Choose **Continue**.
3. An optimization window appears. This may take a few moments to complete.

![Image Assistant Optimize Window](data:image/png;base64,)

1. When you're done, the next tab in Image Assistant, **5\. Configure Image**, automatically displays.

Configure Image

## **[Configure the image](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imageassistant/configimage"%20\l%20"configure-the-image)**

In this step, choose an image name and finish creating your image.

1. The focus of the Image Assistant moves to the **5\. CONFIGURE IMAGE** tab. Enter the following information.

**[Edit Image Details](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imageassistant/configimage"%20\l%20"edit-image-details)**

| **Option** | **Value** |
| --- | --- |
| **Name** | Any unique name identifier for you image, such as _Lab_Image_Chrome_Notepad_v1_ |
| **Display Name** | Any user-friendly name that you can easily identify in the console, such as _Lab Image Chrome Notepad++_ |
| **Description** | Optional text box for a detailed description of your image. You might enter details like applications, versions, creator, date. |
| **Tags** | Leave blank |
| **Always use latest agent version** | Leave clear (unchecked) |

**[Naming Syntax](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imageassistant/configimage"%20\l%20"naming-syntax)**

The **Name** and **Display Name** fields are for identification purposes only. You may use any names that are meaningful to you.

The **Name** field's syntax cannot begin with "Amazon," "AWS," or "AppStream," but you can use any combination of these characters:

- - Lowercase letters (a-z)
    - Uppercase letters (A-Z)
    - Numbers (0-9)
    - Non-alphanumeric characters (_ and -)

The Display Name field's syntax does not have these restrictions. You can use any non-alphanumeric characters as well as spaces between characters.

1. Once you have entered the image details, choose **Next**.

![Image Assistant Configure Image](data:image/png;base64,)  
Review and Create

## **[Review and create the image](https://catalog.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/workshops/e324c13e-2ded-4da2-ad9c-f685305156ac/en-US/imageassistant/review"%20\l%20"review-and-create-the-image)**

In this step, you review the image details, you are disconnected from the remote session, and the image creation process starts.

1. Verify the image details are appropriately configured and choose **Disconnect and Create Image**.

![Image Assistant Create Image](data:image/png;base64,)

1. The remote session is immediately disconnected, leaving you with a Lost Connectivity message in your browser. Close that browser window because the image creation process has started, and you will not be able to reconnect while the image is being created.

![Image Assistant Lost Connectivity](data:image/png;base64,)

1. The image creation process takes about 15 minutes to complete. If it is not still open, reopen the [Amazon AppStream 2.0 console](https://console.aws.amazon.com/appstream2) .
2. In the navigation pane, choose **Images** and then choose the **Image builder** tab. During this process, your image builder displays a status of **Snapshotting** while it is being created.

![Image Snapshotting](data:image/png;base64,)

1. Choose the **Image Registry** tab. In the Filter by attribute or keyword box select **Visibility=Private**. Your image will appear with the status **Available** when it is done snapshotting.

![Image Available](data:image/png;base64,)

Your custom image can now be used to create a fleet. You can now proceed to the next section.
